data.content:
Here's the full migration analysis and replacement code.

## Pattern Classification

| API Found | Pattern | Replacement |
|-----------|---------|-------------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | Cancellable work loop | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Control flow cleanup | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Continue after abort | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` |
| `Thread.Sleep(2000)` + Abort | Timeout enforcement | `Thread.Join(timeout)` + cooperative cancel |

## Why This Breaks on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — it **cannot** forcibly terminate a thread. The entire design must shift from *preemptive* (runtime injects exception) to *cooperative* (code voluntarily checks for cancellation).

## Migrated Code

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(_cts.Token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                var item = GetNextItem(token); // pass token so blocking call can be interrupted
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Cancellation was requested — clean up partial work
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                break; // exit the loop (replaces Thread.ResetAbort + loop continuation)
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null || _workerThread is null)
            return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Wait up to 2 seconds for the thread to finish gracefully
        if (!_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2)))
        {
            // Thread didn't stop in time — log a warning.
            // In cooperative cancellation there is no forced kill;
            // if this happens, GetNextItem or ProcessItem is not
            // honoring the token (see pitfalls below).
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
    }
}
```

## Critical Changes You Must Also Make

### 1. `GetNextItem()` must accept and honor the token

This is the **#1 pitfall** — the original comment says it "may block." If it blocks forever, cancellation never fires.

```csharp
// BEFORE (.NET Framework) — blocks indefinitely, relied on Thread.Abort to escape
private WorkItem GetNextItem()
{
    return _queue.Take(); // blocks until an item is available
}

// AFTER (.NET 8) — unblocks when token is cancelled
private WorkItem GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException on cancel
}
```

If you're using a `ManualResetEvent` or similar:
```csharp
// BEFORE
_signal.WaitOne(); // blocks, only Thread.Abort could break this

// AFTER
WaitHandle.WaitAny(new[] { _signal, token.WaitHandle }); // wakes on cancel
token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested();
```

### 2. `ProcessItem()` — add checkpoints for long work

```csharp
private void ProcessItem(WorkItem item, CancellationToken token)
{
    foreach (var step in item.Steps)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint between steps
        ExecuteStep(step);
    }
}
```

## Key Pitfalls for This Code

| Pitfall | Details |
|---------|---------|
| **Blocking `GetNextItem` ignores token** | If `GetNextItem` doesn't accept a `CancellationToken`, `Stop()` will hang at `Join()`. The token must be threaded through to whatever blocks. |
| **No forced kill exists** | If `Join(2000)` times out, you cannot force-stop the thread. The only recourse is logging + moving truly uncooperative code to a child `Process` and calling `Process.Kill`. |
| **`CancellationTokenSource` must be disposed** | It holds timer/callback resources. The `IDisposable` pattern above handles this. |
| **`ResetAbort` loop continuation is gone** | The old code caught the abort, rolled back, and *continued the loop*. The migrated code **breaks** out instead. If you need to continue processing after a per-item cancellation, use a *linked* token per work item (see below). |

### If you need per-item cancellation (continue loop after rollback)

```csharp
private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken shutdownToken)
{
    while (!shutdownToken.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        // Per-item token linked to the shutdown token
        using var itemCts = CancellationTokenSource.CreateLinkedTokenSource(shutdownToken);
        itemCts.CancelAfter(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30)); // per-item timeout

        try
        {
            var item = GetNextItem(shutdownToken);
            ProcessItem(item, itemCts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (!shutdownToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // Per-item timeout, not a shutdown — rollback and continue
            RollbackCurrentTransaction();
        }
        finally
        {
            FlushBuffers();
        }
    }
}
```

The `when (!shutdownToken.IsCancellationRequested)` filter distinguishes a per-item timeout from a full shutdown — the latter falls through and exits the loop.
